In Ruby, a singleton method is a method defined for only one specific object, not for all instances of its class.

Let’s understand using your example:

obj = "hello"

def obj.greet
  p "hi!"
end
What happened here?

obj is an instance of String

Normally, methods defined in class String are available to all strings

But greet is defined only for this particular object "hello"

So:

obj.greet   # => "hi!"

But:

"world".greet
# => NoMethodError

Because greet exists only on that single object.

🔹 Why is it called "singleton"?

Because the method belongs to a single (one) object, not to the whole class.

Ruby internally creates a hidden class for that object called a:

Singleton class

Eigenclass

Metaclass

🔹 How Ruby Internally Thinks

When you write:

def obj.greet

Ruby actually does something like this internally:

class << obj
  def greet
    p "hi!"
  end
end

This opens the object's singleton class and defines the method there.

🔹 Real-World Example
user1 = "Shubham"
user2 = "Rahul"

def user1.admin?
  true
end

user1.admin?  # => true
user2.admin?  # => NoMethodError

Only user1 has that method.

🔹 Important Difference

| Normal Method              | Singleton Method             |
| -------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Defined inside class       | Defined on specific object   |
| Available to all instances | Available to only one object |

🔹 Why Ruby Allows This?

Because Ruby is a pure object-oriented language — even classes themselves are objects.

For example:

class User
end

def User.info
  "I am a class method"
end

Here User.info is actually a singleton method on the class object User.

So in Ruby:

Class methods are just singleton methods defined on a class object.